\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
SHV coaxial feedthrough RCR filter
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Eric L.
 Martin
\end_layout

\begin_layout Address
Triangle Universities Nuclear Laboratory, Durham, NC 27708, USA
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
This filter is intended for use biasing germanium detectors for the LEGEND
 experiment, where the load current is expected to be < 1 nA and a large
 series resistance is acceptable.
 The final filter characteristics are 100 MΩ input resistance, 100 MΩ output
 resistance, and 16 nF capacitance to ground.
 The expected capacitance between input and output is 0.13 pF.
 The filter is constructed to minimize radiation power transfer by keeping
 the input on the same axis as the output and keeping the ground current
 symmetric about the output axis so capacitor radiation is emitted perpendicular
 to the output axis and cancels.
 The entire filter is contained in a sealed tube that can be filled with
 oil and mounts on a front-side nut SHV bulkhead jack.
 The SHV jack uses a gasket seal and is suitable for use in an oil filled
 application.
 The final diameter is 3/4 inches with a length behind the bulkhead of 3-1/2
 inches to the output cable.
 The mounting hole is a common 1/2 inch D shaped standard.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Part*
\begin_inset Newpage pagebreak
\end_inset

Parts:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
1 SHV bulkhead jack, TE Connectivity AMP Connectors 5225059-3.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
1 3/4 inch OD 0.032 inch wall copper 101 tube cut to 3.16 inches.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
6 2.7 nF 6 kV ceramic capacitors, Vishay Vitramon HV2225Y272KX6ATHV.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
1 11/16 inch OD 1/4 inch ID copper washer.
 Hillman 44142.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
1 M4 brass standoff in 6 mm hex, 5 or 6 mm length.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
2 100 MΩ 7.5 kV axial lead resistors, Ohmite MOX1125231006FE.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Epoxy, Loctite Hysol EA 0151.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Enumerate
The epoxy needs to be able to withstand high enough temperature to solder
 the SHV jack housing with the pin installed, this will heat the epoxy to
 somewhere around 200 C for a few minutes depending on the solder used.
 Most epoxies can handle such temperature for a short time.
 The epoxy should also be able to handle short term exposure to isopropyl
 alcohol and long term exposure to silicone oil.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
20 mL of silicone oil, Super Lube 45NA65.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Section of high voltage cable for the output.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Section of wire braid to shield the output cable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Copper tube to cover resistor to output cable joint, cut piece of AWG 20
 wire terminal crimp connector.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Electrical tape.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
M2.5 washer, or something similar to use as a temporary spacer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
4 mm grommet, printed part.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Tube jig, printed part.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Capacitor jig, printed part.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Part*
Assembly
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Assemble the input resistor and SHV jack
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Prepare the SHV bulkhead jack
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The nickel plating on the SHV jack body is difficult to solder to while
 the underlying brass is far easier.
 It is a thin layer and will take little effort to remove.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Tape over the opening in the SHV jack body to prevent any metal from getting
 into the connector.
 Stray bits of metal can cause discharge problems later.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Remove the nickel layer around the largest diameter surface of the SHV jack
 body with a file, this is where the tube will later be soldered.
 See figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:SHVjackPlating"
