	filename FilterInternalInsertion.jpg
	lyxscale 30
	width 5in

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename FinalCapacitorSoldering.jpg
	lyxscale 30
	height 2in

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename FinalBraidSoldering.jpg
	lyxscale 30
	height 2in

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Filter assembly just before tube is slide into position.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Heat the tube right next to the holes and feed solder into the hole until
 it flows in and joints the tube to the capacitor.
 Make sure the holes are filled, these are oil boundries.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Solder the SHV jack to the tube.
 Ensure there are no gaps as this is an oil seal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Solder the end of the braid to the washer, make sure no stray wires go into
 the hole that could cause discahrges.
 This gap will be filled with epoxy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\size large
4.3 Clean solder with a heavy-duty flux remover
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Materials needed: Acetone, glass beaker, syringe with needle tip, gloves,
 lab and glasses.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To ensure that all the flux is removed and does not contribute to the discharges
, it is recommended to clean the solder components, especially the pulser
 board, with heavy duty flux removal.
 The compound used is Acetone, which is highly flammable.
 Gloves and glasses must be worn at all time while handling Acetone, and
 cure must be maintained to not breathe in the Acetone fumes.
 Use only small amount of Acetone at times.
 Acetone can disolve plastic.
 Thus it is important to not let Acetone touch the 3D printed endcaps and
 end ground break insulator to the SHV pin.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Pour a small amount of Acetone into the beaker.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Draw Acetone into the syringe 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
While holding the file with the pulse board on the bottom, put some Acetone
 into the filter using the small port holes 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Swirl for a few seconds.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Repeat one more time to ensure all flux is removed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Carefully pour the Acetone/flux solution back into a beaker.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Use a KimTech wipe to wipe down Acetone around the filter 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Use an empty syringe to purge the filter several times with air.
 This will helpd dry out remaining Acetone.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let the filter dry for atleast an hour.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let over Acetone in the cup evaporate in a well ventilated area, idially
 the fume hood in room 163.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Sealing the cable connection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Hold the filter connector end up and flow isopropyl alcohol in through the
 fill hole, letting it drain out the gap between the washer and cable.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
This is the last chance to clean the filter by flushing fluid through the
 filter.
 Unless an optional drain hole is added to the output end of the filter
 it can only be cleaned by filling and draining through the same hole, which
 won't be as effective, once the cable connection is sealed.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Mix some epoxy and apply it generously to the gap between the washer and
 cable.
 It isn't critical to keep the expoy from flowing into the filter but the
 point is to seal the gap, not pot the filter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Slide the cable grommet into position to hold the epoxy in while it cures.
 Any voids in the epoxy on the filter exterior side of the washer will not
 be exposed to high electric field and are of no concern for discharges.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Tape around to grommet to ensure the epoxy remains in place while it cures.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Hold the filter connector end up so the epoxy flows into the gap and seals
 as it cures.
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

